rdens and the brooding black ",{"type":"'''","value":["Okayama Castle"]},"."]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Shimonoseki"]]}," - gateway to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Kyushu"]]}," and the Kanmon Straits, best known for turning poisonous fish into gourmet meals."]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Tottori"]]}," - Home to Japan's only sand dunes, the ",{"type":"'''","value":["Tottori Sand Dunes"]}," provide visitors with a highly unique experience, including camel rides."]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Yamaguchi"]]}," - a city with many well-preserved temples."]},"\n",{"type":"==","value":["Other destinations"]},"\n\n",{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Akiyoshidai"]]}," - has the largest plateau and cave in Japan."]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Bizen"]]}," - home to Japan's oldest and most respected style of pottery."]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Daisen (Tottori)"],["Daisen"]]}," - climbers flock to the beautiful ",{"type":"'''","value":["Mount Daisen"]},"."]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Iwakuni"]]}," - a town with the picturesque ",{"type":"'''","value":["Kintai-kyo Bridge"]},"."]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Miyajima"]]}," - Location of ",{"type":"'''","value":["Itsukushima Shrine"]},", the most photographed shrine in all of Japan."]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Oda"],["Iwami Ginzan"]]}," - Silver mines, registered as a ",{"type":"[[","value":[["UNESCO World Heritage Site"]]},"."]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Onomichi"]]}," - hillside town with pleasant paths connecting dozens of small temples."]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Takahashi"]]}," - a quaint town most famous for ",{"type":"'''","value":["Bitchu Matsuyama Castle"]},"."]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Tsuyama"]]}," - a relaxed town famous for the thousands of cherry blossoms around its castle ruins in ",{"type":"'''","value":["Kakuzan Park"]},"."]},"\n",{"type":"==","value":["Understand"]},"\n\nThe name ",{"type":"''","value":["Chūgoku"]}," literally means \"Middle Country\", the sole surviving relic of a historical division of Japan into \"Near Countries\" (近国 ",{"type":"''","value":["Kingoku"]},"), \"Middle Countries\" and \"Far Countries\" (遠国 ",{"type":"''","value":["Ongoku"]},"), based on distance from the capital ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Kyoto"]]},". Strictly speaking, today's Chugoku covers only the Middle Countries along the San'indo and San'yodo roads, and hence ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Okayama Prefecture"],["Okayama"]]}," is sometimes not considered a full part of Chugoku, as only three of its five component provinces (Mimasaka, Bizen and Bitchu) were Middle Countries.\n\nIn ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Japanese phrasebook"],["Japanese"]]},", the characters 中国 and the reading ",{"type":"''","value":["Chūgoku"]}," are also used to mean \"",{"type":"[[","value":[["China"]]},"\". (The same characters are used in Chinese, but pronounced ",{"type":"''","value":["Zhongguo"]},".)  However, as the Chugoku region is always referred to with the qualifier \"-chihō\" and the ",{"type":"[[","value":[["People's Republic of China"]]}," and ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Republic of China"]]}," can be referenced by their full names, there is usually little scope for confusion.\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Talk"]},"\t \n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Get in"]},"\n\n",{"type":"===","value":["By plane"]},"\n\n",{"type":"[[","value":[["Hiroshima"]]},", ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Okayama"]]},", and ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Yonago"]]}," offer both domestic and international connections with other cities in ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Asia"]]},".\n\n",{"type":"[[","value":[["Izumo"]]},", ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Masuda"]]},", ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Yamaguchi"]]},", and ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Tottori"]]}," each offer domestic flights.\n\n",{"type":"===","value":["By train"]},"\n\nThe ",{"type":"'''","value":["San'yo Shinkansen"]}," line links ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Hiroshima"]]},", ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Okayama"]]}," and other major towns to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Kyushu"]]}," in the southwest and ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Kansai"]]}," (",{"type":"[[","value":[["Osaka"]]},") to the east. The less populated northern Japan Sea coast is served by ordinary train services.\n\n",{"type":"===","value":["By ferry"]},"\n",{"type":"*","value":["Ferries from ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Shimonoseki"]]}," Port International Terminal"]},{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"*","value":["The Kanpu ferry to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Pusan"]]}," in ",{"type":"[[","value":[["South Korea"]]}," regularly."]}]},{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"*","value":["The Orient ferry to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Qingdao"]]}," in ",{"type":"[[","value":[["China"]]}," regularly."]}]},{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"*","value":["The Orient ferry to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Shanghai"]]}," in ",{"type":"[[","value":[["China"]]}," regularly."]}]},"\n",{"type":"==","value":["Get around"]},"\n",{"type":"===","value":["By train"]},"\nThe ",{"type":"'''","value":[{"type":"[","value":["http:\/\/www.jr-odekake.net\/en\/jwrp\/sanyo.html JR West San'yo Area Pass"]}]}," allows unlimited travel along the San'yo Shinkansen and San'yo main line west of Osaka, including the Shinkansen (even Nozomi and Mizuho trains).  The 4-day\/8-day pass is ¥20,000\/30,000. An enhanced version of this pass, the ",{"type":"'''","value":[{"type":"[","value":["http:\/\/www.jr-odekake.net\/en\/jwrp\/all_kyushu.html San'yo-Shikoku-Kyushu Pass"]}]},", also includes travel to Shikoku and all or part of Kyushu. 5-day consecutive passes range from ¥22-25,000.\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["See"]},"\n",{"type":"===","value":["World Heritage Sites"]},"\nThe Chugoku region is home to three of Japan's ",{"type":"[[","value":[["UNESCO World Heritage Sites"]]},":\n",{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"'''","value":["Iwami Ginzan Silver Mine and Its Cultural Landscape"]}," (",{"type":"[[","value":[["Oda"]]},") - Registered as a World Heritage Site in 2007."]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"'''","value":["Hiroshima Peace Memorial (Genbaku Dome)"]}," (",{"type":"[[","value":[["Hiroshima"]]},") - Registered as a World Heritage Site in 1996."]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"'''","value":["Itsukushima Shrine"]}," (",{"type":"[[","value":[["Miyajima"]]},") - Registered as a World Heritage Site in 1996."]},"\n",{"type":"===","value":["Castles"]},"\n",{"type":"====","value":["Original Castles"]},"\n\nOnly twelve original castles remain in Japan, and the Chugoku region is home to two of them:\n",{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"'''","value":["Bitchu Matsuyama Castle"]}," (",{"type":"[[","value":[["Takahashi"]]},") - Japan's highest castle."]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"'''","value":["Matsue Castle"]},"(",{"type":"[[","value":[["Matsue"]]},") - One of Japan's few black castles."]},"\n",{"type":"====","value":["Reconstructed Castles"]},"\n",{"type":"*","value":[" Okayama Castle, ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Okayama"]]}]},{"type":"*","value":[" Hiroshima Castle, ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Hiroshima"]]}]},{"type":"*","value":[" Fukuyama Castle, ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Fukuyama"]]}]},{"type":"*","value":[" Iwakuni Castle, ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Iwakuni"]]}]},{"type":"*","value":[" Mihara Castle, ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Mihara"]]}]},{"type":"*","value":[" Kawahara Castle, ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Tottori"]]}]},"\n",{"type":"====","value":["Castle Ruins"]},"\n",{"type":"*","value":[" Kakuzan Park (Tsuyama Castle), ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Tsuyama"]]}]},{"type":"*","value":[" Tottori Castle, ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Tottori"]]}]},{"type":"*","value":[" Tsuwano Castle, ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Tsuwano"]]}]},{"type":"*","value":[" Hagi Castle, ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Hagi"]]}]},{"type":"*","value":[" Shimotsui Castle, ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Kurashiki"],["Kurashiki (Kojima area)"]]}]},"\n",{"type":"===","value":["Gardens"]},"\nThis is a list of some of the areas most famous gardens however, there are many other beautiful gardens throughout the region:\n",{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"'''","value":["Korakuen Garden"]}," (",{"type":"[[","value":[["Okayama"]]},") This is the most famous garden in the Chugoku region, as well as one of the ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Japan's Top 3"],["top three gardens"]]}," in all of Japan."]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"'''","value":["RSK Rose Garden"]}," (",{"type":"[[","value":[["Okayama"]]},") A large garden containing a wide variety of roses from all over the world."]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"'''","value":["Shurakuen Garden"]}," (",{"type":"[[","value":[["Tsuyama"]]},") A beautiful 17th century garden with no entry fee."]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"'''","value":["Miyama English Garden"]}," (",{"type":"[[","value":[["Tamano"]]},") An authentic English garden created by the British man Peter Thurman"]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"'''","value":["Adachi Museum of Art"]}," (",{"type":"[[","value":[["Yasugi"]]},") Although there is a museum displaying over 1,000 works of art, the highlight of the museum for many is not the museum; it's the garden. Constructed in 1980, the garden is quite new but what it lacks in history it makes up for in size and beauty. This garden has been voted the best garden in Japan by the American Journal of Japanese Gardening."]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"'''","value":["Vogel Park"]}," (",{"type":"[[","value":[["Matsue"]]},") One of the largest greenhouses in the world, as well as an aviary."]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"'''","value":["Yuushien Garden"]}," (",{"type":"[[","value":[["Matsue"]]},") Built for beauty in every season, including winter when the camellia's bloom."]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"'''","value":["Enchoen Chinese Garden"]}," (",{"type":"[[","value":[["Yurihama"]]},") One of the largest Chinese gardens in Japan. Enchoen was first built in ",{"type":"[[","value":[["China"]]},", disassembled, and then rebuilt in ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Yurihama"]]}," as a symbol of friendship between ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Tottori (prefecture)"],["Tottori"]]}," and China's ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Hebei Province"]]},"."]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"'''","value":["Tulip Fields"]}," (",{"type":"[[","value":[["Hiezu"]]},") A garden full of beautiful red and yellow tulips."]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"'''","value":["Shukkeien Garden"]}," (",{"type":"[[","value":[["Hiroshima"]]},") An impressive garden built by Ueda Soko, considered to be one of the greatest masters of the tea ceremony."]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"'''","value":["Sesshutei Garden"]}," (",{"type":"[[","value":[["Yamaguchi"]]},") This garden is a reproduction of a scene from one of Sesshu's most famous landscape paintings."]},{"type":"*","value":[{"type":"'''","value":["Chōfu Garden"]}," (",{"type":"[[","value":[["Shimonoseki"]]},")  One of the famous gardens in Castle town Chōfu."]},"\n",{"type":"===","value":[" Temples and Shrines"]},"\n",{"type":"[[","value":[["File:Japan Tottori MitokuSan Nageiredo DSC01248.jpg"],["thumb"],["right"],["200px"],["Sanbutsuji Temple"]]},"\nAlthough temples and shrines can be found in abundance throughout the region, these are some of the most important and most interesting temples and shrines in the Chugoku Region.\n\n",{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"'''","value":["Izumo Shrine"]}," (",{"type":"[[","value":[["Izumo"]]},") The second holiest Shinto shrine  (Ise Shrine in ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Ise"]]}," being number one) and certainly one o the most impressive in Japan Izumo Shrine is dedicated to the god of marriage and happiness. "]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"'''","value":["Itsukushima Shrine"]}," (",{"type":"[[","value":[["Miyajima"]]},") As Japan's most photographed shrine, one of the ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Japan's Top 3"],["top three